description: The Tribeca Festival in New York City features powerful examples of storytelling through the use of virtual reality, augmented reality, artificial intelligence, interactive media and other technologies.
title: At Tribeca Festival, VR and other tech fuels immersive storytelling

description: The previous roster of the CDC's vaccine advisers were fired on Monday.
title: RFK Jr. taps allies, COVID vaccine critics among picks for CDC advisory panel

description: As the U.S. exits northern Syria, Russia is emerging as the new power broker in the region. Charlie D'Agata is following developments in neighboring Iraq and has more on the pace of the U.S. withdrawal.
title: U.S. military pulls out of Syrian bases

description: Florida firefighter Daryl Paul has found a way to turn old fire hoses into works of art. His creations feature the American flag. Manuel Bojorquez has his story.
title: Firefighter turns old fire hoses into works of art

description: LeBron James is under fire after making comments that appeared to side with the Chinese government against Hong Kong. In response, protesters in Hong Kong burned and trampled his jersey. Jonathan Vigliotti reports.
title: LeBron James facing backlash over China comments

description: With American soldiers scrambling to get out of Syria, Russia is advancing. "Face the Nation" moderator Margaret Brennan joins the "CBS Evening News" to discuss the president's strategy.
title: What is Trump's Syria strategy?

description: The House impeachment inquiry continued behind closed doors. The committees have been hearing from administration officials, past and present. A lot of the questions center around the work of the president's lawyer, Rudy Giuliani. Nancy Cordes has the latest.
title: Trump defends Giuliani amid impeachment inquiry

description: British teen Harry Dunn was killed in a traffic accident involving American Anne Sacoolas. During a trip to the White House, Dunn's parents said the president surprised them with an offer to meet Sacoolas. Imtiaz Tyab explains.
title: Parents of U.K. teen felt “ambushed” by White House visit

description: More than 60 million Americans will feel the effects of a nor'easter. Torrential rain and powerful gusts are expected. Climate and weather contributor Jeff Berardelli has the latest on the storm.
title: Millions of Americans in the path of nor'easter

description: It was Senator Elizabeth Warren and not Joe Biden, who got most of the attention at the latest Democratic debate. Biden now trails Warren in early primary states and some national polls. Ed O'Keefe reports.
title: Warren faces attacks from Democratic opponents during debate

description: President Trump faced condemnation from both Democrats and Republicans for essentially greenlighting a Turkish assault on a key U.S. ally in the fight against terror. More than two thirds of Republicans joined Democrats in a House vote to oppose the president's action. Paula Reid reports.
title: House condemns Trump's Syria withdrawal

description: The acting White House chief of staff said a delay in millions of dollars in aid to Ukraine was due to concerns about corruption. Mick Mulvaney's comments sparked a firestorm, and he is now trying to walk them back. Nancy Cordes has the latest.
title: Mulvaney says delay in Ukraine aid linked to DOJ investigation

description: A teenager in Maine is fighting a suspension after warning classmates about an alleged rapist at school. School officials said her warning amounted to bullying. Errol Barnett reports.
title: Teen fighting suspension over rape-awareness note

description: Dashcam video shows the moments a Utah trooper pulled an unconscious man from a car stopped on train tracks. He had just seconds before a train was set to crash into them. Carter Evans explains.
title: Utah trooper rescues man from oncoming train

description: The fallout continues after a black woman was shot and killed by a former officer in her own home. At a city council meeting, residents called for a change in policing tactics. Omar Villafranca reports.
title: Fort Worth residents demand action after deadly police shooting

description: President Trump's decision to hold the next G-7 summit at one of his private resorts in Florida is raising concerns. Some say the president is profiting from his position of power. Major Garrett reports.
title: White House says next G-7 summit will be at Trump property

description: CBS News has confirmed that former Massachusetts Governor Deval Patrick is considering running for president in 2020. CBS News political correspondent Ed O'Keefe speaks to CBSN's Tanya Rivero about the impact he would have on the Democratic primary race.
title: Deval Patrick considering running for president

description: Vice President Mike Pence announced that Turkish President Erdogan agreed to a ceasefire in northern Syria. The president called it a "great day for civilization." Charlie D'Agata reports from Iraq.
title: Kurd commander accepts ceasefire terms

description: There are fears of another possible collapse at a construction site in New Orleans where a new Hard Rock Hotel is being built. A new video shows workers were concerned about the safety of the structure. Omar Villafranca explains.
title: Video shows workers were concerned days before Hard Rock Hotel collapse

description: Tropical Storm Nestor could strengthen into a Category 1 hurricane before it makes landfall along the Florida Panhandle. WCBS chief weathercaster Lonnie Quinn is tracking the storm.
title: Tropical Storm Nestor eyes the Gulf Coast

description: In Chicago, teachers walked off the job in a massive strike. But the city is warning their demands are too costly. Meg Oliver reports.
title: Thousands of Chicago teachers go on strike

description: A monumental new biography of Thomas Edison is set to be released this week. The author is one of the greatest non-fiction writers of our time, Edmund Morris, who died this May at the age of 78, just after the book was finished. His wife, Sylvia Jukes Morris, is a biographer herself. Jeff Glor reports.
title: Sylvia Jukes Morris on her husband's legacy and what drew them both to biographies

description: Inclined sleepers for infants have been controversial since Fisher-Price invented them more than a decade ago. A new study out confirms the design is dangerous and deadly. Anna Werner reports.
title: Study finds Rock 'n Play design led to deaths

description: There have been 420 spacewalks and at least one man has taken part in every one of them. But astronauts Christina Koch and Jessica Meir are about to change history. Mark Strassmann explains.
title: Astronauts ready for historic all-female spacewalk

description: A first-of-its-kind law went into effect in Philadelphia this month, mandating that all businesses accept physical dollar bills or coins in exchange for goods and services. Overall, the percentage of cash payments in the U.S. has been dropping, from 33% to 26% in just the past four years. That's prompted some businesses to go entirely cashless. But not everyone is buying in. Brook Silva-Braga reports.
title: The backlash against going cashless

description: The reward is growing in the case of a missing 3-year-old Alabama girl. It's up to $33,000 in the search for Kamille "Cupcake" McKinney.
title: Reward increased for missing Alabama toddler

description: The Environmental Protection Agency has proposed cutting regulations that curb air pollution from fossil fuel power plants. The Biden administration put the rules in place to fight climate change. CBS News national environmental correspondent David Schechter explains the significance of the announcement.
title: EPA proposes rolling back rules on power plant pollution

description: Nearly eight years ago, Louisiana Republican Steve Scalise, now the House majority leader, was at a practice for the congressional baseball game when a rifle-wielding left-wing extremist shot him. CBS News chief Washington correspondent Major Garrett stopped by the field Wednesday morning to chat with Scalise about his survival story and the latest political headlines.
title: House Majority Leader Scalise reflects on 2017 congressional baseball shooting

description: Egg prices declined again in May, but still remain substantially higher than they were a year ago as avian flu remains on the loose.
title: Egg prices for consumers fell to 5-month low in May. Here's why.

description: America's senior diplomat in Ukraine is testifying, laying out what Democrats are calling "damning" allegations against the president. Bill Taylor described a secret campaign to pressure Ukraine, using U.S. aid as bait. Nancy Cordes reports.
title: Top diplomat in Ukraine gives "damning" testimony

description: When K-9 D'Jango was shot by a suspect, he was rushed to a veterinary hospital for emergency surgery. Officers never left his side, just like thy do for injured human officers. Mola Lenghi has more.
title: Officers line up for hero K-9 recovering from shooting

description: A suspected gunman is under arrest, hours after a shooting at a California school. One teenager was wounded in Santa Rosa, about 55 miles north of San Francisco.
title: Suspect arrested after California school shooting

description: Detailed, damning and disturbing — that's how House Democrats described the almost 10-hours of testimony given by Bill Taylor, the top U.S. diplomat in Ukraine, as part of the impeachment inquiry. Taylor laid out in detail his account of how President Trump held up military aid for Ukraine, pushing President Zelensky to investigate Democrats and a company linked to the son of former Vice President Joe Biden. Nancy Cordes reports.
title: Top U.S. diplomat in Ukraine describes "alarming" Ukraine pressure campaign

description: In 1946, a white mob in Georgia murdered two black couples. No one was charged, but now there's a fight to open sealed records linked to the case. Mark Strassmann reports.
title: Activists hope for answers in 1946 lynchings

description: "Queer Eye" star Karamo is known for helping people work through their emotions. But it's his own experience with severe depression, anxiety and drug addiction that's helped him become an advocate for mental health. Karamo joins "CBS This Morning's" special "Stop the Stigma" broadcast to discuss why he used to think mental health support was only for "rich white people." He says he even thought of taking his own life.
title: Stop the Stigma: Karamo on mental health in minority communities, setting emotional goals

description: A judge said the Trump administration cannot detain or deport Mahmoud Khalil for the foreign policy reasons cited by the Trump administration.
title: Judge rules Mahmoud Khalil cannot be deported based on Rubio determination

description: Legendary journalist Gwen Ifill is being honored with a stamp. Ifill, who died three years ago, was a trailblazer in print and broadcast journalism.
title: Journalist Gwen Ifill honored with stamp

description: Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg is scheduled to testify Wednesday on Capitol Hill. The hearing is supposed to be about cryptocurrency, but congressional members of both parties are poised to ask him what he's been doing about protecting U.S. elections and policing harmful content. Ed O'Keefe reports.
title: Mark Zuckerberg to face lawmakers' questions on protecting elections

description: After more than 30 years reporting the news, Emmy Award-winning broadcast journalist Jane Pauley put a very public face on bipolar disorder. She revealed she had taken a break from the spotlight and spent three weeks in a psychiatric clinic after being diagnosed in 2001. Pauley is an advocate for mental health and the host of "CBS Sunday Morning." She joins "CBS This Morning's" special "Stop the Stigma" broadcast to discuss when she was first diagnosed with bipolar disorder.
title: Jane Pauley says doctor offered her a "cover story" to hide bipolar diagnosis

description: The CDC estimates one out of every six adults will have depression at some point in their lives. Some psychiatrists now recommend a different approach to treatment. As part of the "CBS This Morning" special, "Stop the Stigma: A Conversation About Mental Health," Jamie Yuccas takes a look at the alternative treatment that uses magnetic pulses to stimulate neurons in the brain.
title: How deep transcranial magnetic stimulation changed one woman's life

description: Iraq's defense minister said U.S. troops that were pulled out of Syria will leave Iraq in four weeks. That seems to contradict Defense Secretary Mark Esper, who has said those U.S. forces will continue operating against ISIS. Russia and Turkey made a deal Tuesday, without the U.S., to take control of northeastern Syria and force out Kurdish fighters that fought alongside U.S. troops. Holly Williams reports.
title: Russian troops moving into areas once controlled by US-backed Kurds

description: One in six young people experience a mental health disorder each year, and the suicide rate for adolescents age 10 to 14 has nearly tripled in the last decade. Miana Bryant, who was diagnosed with depression in college, didn't know where to turn, so she created a support group called The Mental Elephant for college students to talk with each other about their mental health. Bryant and NAMI medical director Dr. Ken Duckworth join "CBS This Morning's" special "Stop the Stigma" broadcast to discuss how to find help.
title: How peer groups like Mental Elephant can help young adults with mental illness

description: Boeing is expected to announce major financial losses Wednesday because the grounding of its 737 Max aircraft has lasted longer than expected. The planes have been grounded worldwide since mid-March following two deadly crashes that killed 346 people. On Tuesday, the president and CEO of Boeing's commercial airline division was replaced. Kris Van Cleave reports.
title: Boeing exec Kevin McAllister ousted amid substantial financial losses

description: Lady Gaga's mother, Cynthia Germanotta, joins "CBS This Morning's" special "Stop the Stigma" broadcast to talk about the impact of mental illness on family and friends. Germanotta teamed up with her daughter to create the Born This Way Foundation. It works to educate people about mental and emotional wellness.
title: Lady Gaga's mom on witnessing daughter's "turn" in mental health

description: Mental health disorders are treatable, but last year, nearly 57 percent of those who needed treatment did not get it. For advice on how to find help, psychiatrists Dr. Ken Duckworth and Dr. Sue Varma, along with CBS News chief medical correspondent Dr. Jon LaPook, join "CBS This Morning's" special "Stop the Stigma" broadcast.
title: How to get help for mental illnesses

description: Psychiatrist Dr. Sue Varma joins "CBS This Morning" to discuss why celebrities speaking out on mental health is so important.
title: Dr. Sue Varma on why it's important for celebrities to speak out on mental health

description: Emily Borchardt is part of a class-action lawsuit against Austin law enforcement and other officials, claiming they failed in their duties to bring justice to female sexual assault victims. Attorney Jenny Ecklund said women felt "dismissed."
title: Austin, Texas, officials face class-action lawsuit over handling of rape cases

description: In his only broadcast interview ahead of the release of his new film, "Western Stars," Springsteen sits down with Gayle King for a frank conversation about life, marriage and his career. In this excerpt, they discuss why after all his success he still struggles. Tune in to “CBS This Morning” on Thursday and Friday for more of their conversation.
title: Even Bruce Springsteen still struggles

description: Legendary singer and songwriter Bruce Springsteen tells "CBS This Morning" co-host Gayle King Americans are living in "a frightening time." Springsteen is out with a new film, "Western Stars," which hits theaters nationwide this weekend.
title: Bruce Springsteen: President Trump "doesn't have a grasp" on what it means to be American

description: Across the country, police and prosecutors are using the term "exceptional clearance" to close rape cases, marking them as resolved, even when there's enough evidence to make an arrest. Nikki Battiste reports on how women in Austin, Texas, are fighting back against a system they say has failed them.
title: Police accused of misusing "exceptional clearance" to close rape cases

description: Senate Republicans, led by Lindsey Graham, entered the impeachment fight. He introduced a resolution condemning the House for a lack of transparency in the impeachment inquiry. Nancy Cordes reports.
title: Senate Republicans introduce resolution condemning Democrats on impeachment

description: In a "60 Minutes" interview with Norah O'Donnell, Joe Biden addressed his son's business dealings in Ukraine. He also unleashed his sharpest criticism yet on President Trump's family.
title: Joe Biden says his children won't "have offices in the White House"

description: An investigation is underway in Britain after more than three dozen bodies were found in a semi-truck. The discovery was made early Wednesday morning in an industrial park in the county of Essex, east of London. Police say the victims include 38 adults and one teenager. A 25-year-old man from Northern Ireland, who was driving the truck, was arrested on suspicion of murder.
title: 39 bodies discovered in truck in England

description: In his only broadcast interview ahead of the release of his new film, "Western Stars," Springsteen sits down with Gayle King for a frank conversation about life, marriage and his career. In this excerpt, they discuss why he still finds performing "psychologically centering." Tune in to “CBS This Morning” on Thursday and Friday for more of their conversation.
title: Bruce Springsteen still finds performing therapeutic

description: Brian Wilson was one of the world's most influential recording artists.
title: Brian Wilson, the Beach Boys visionary leader, dies at age 82

description: The Trump administration is following through with plans to roll back federal limits on carbon and air pollution from fossil fuel power plants. CBS News Climate Unit senior coordinating producer Tracy Wholf has more.
title: Trump rolling back federal power plant pollution limits

description: Billionaire and former New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg has filed for the 2020 Democratic primary in Arkansas. John Harris, editor-in-chief and co-founder of Politico, joins CBSN with the latest on the 2020 race.
title: Michael Bloomberg files for Democratic primary in Arkansas

description: Two career diplomats will testify Wednesday in the first public hearings in the impeachment inquiry. This comes as CBS News polls show more than half of Americans are upset with how both House Democrats and President Trump are handling the inquiry. CBS News' Nikole Killion and Bloomberg chief Washington correspondent Kevin Cirilli join CBSN to explain what to expect ahead of Wednesday's hearings.
title: Lawmakers prepare strategy for public impeachment hearings

description: More than 700,000 young immigrants who grew up in the U.S. could be at risk of deportation if the Supreme Court doesn't rule in their favor. CBS News immigration reporter Camilo Montoya-Galvez explains how President Trump's termination of the Obama-era DACA program could affect "Dreamers" across the U.S.
title: Supreme Court hears arguments on "Dreamers" in DACA case

description: More than 220 million Americans are bracing for sub-zero temperatures as a brutal arctic blast sweeps across much of the country. CBS News weather producer David Parkinson has more on what to expect in the coming days.
title: Arctic blast threatens millions of Americans

description: Former President Jimmy Carter was hospitalized in Atlanta late Monday for a surgical procedure to relieve pressure on his brain. This comes after the 95-year-old suffered several falls that triggered swelling in his brain. Dr. Janette Nesheiwat joined CBSN to discuss the risks of the procedure.
title: Risks of former President Jimmy Carter's operation for brain pressure

description: Recycled footage, a video game clip and debunked rumors have spread online, fueling misinformation about L.A. protests
title: Fake videos and conspiracies fuel falsehoods about L.A. protests

description: Melanie Coleman, a 20-year-old competitive gymnast at Southern Connecticut State University, died after suffering a serious spinal injury in a fall from the uneven bars. WFSB-TV's Matt McFarland reports.
title: College gymnast dies in training accident

description: Instagram announced it is hiding some "likes" on posts in the U.S. starting this week. The social media platform says this is part of a test to see how it can improve the well-being of its users. Sara Fischer, media reporter for Axios, joined CBSN to discuss.
title: Instagram hiding "likes" on some posts in the U.S.

description: The African Meeting House located in Boston's Beacon Hill area is facing some tough budget cuts, but a second grade class is trying to help save it.
title: Second graders trying to save African Meeting House in Boston

description: A new CBS News poll shows 43% of Americans say President Trump deserves impeachment, while 40% say he does not. This comes as Congress prepares for the first public hearings in the impeachment inquiry Wednesday. CBS News chief congressional correspondent Nancy Cordes joined CBSN with the latest.
title: CBS News poll: 43% of Americans say Trump deserves to be impeached

description: The Supreme Court will hear arguments that could decide the fate of 700,000 young undocumented immigrants who came to the U.S. as children. The Trump administration is fighting to end the Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals program, known as DACA. CBS News immigration reporter Camilo Montoya-Galvez joined CBSN to discuss the impact this could have on thousands of "Dreamers."
title: Supreme Court considers Trump's DACA rejection

description: A new study finds people whose income dropped by at least 50% were significantly more likely to have a cardiovascular event compared to those whose income went up. CBS News medical contributor Dr. Tara Narula, a board certified cardiologist, joined CBSN AM to explain.
title: How your paycheck may impact your heart health

description: A new report suggests Google has been secretly collecting the personal health records of millions of Americans. As first reported in the Wall Street Journal, Google is sharing information with Ascension, a health system that includes over 2,600 hospitals and health care centers in 21 states. Dr. Tara Narula reports.
title: Google reportedly mining personal health data raises privacy concerns

description: A brutal arctic blast is making its descent on the U.S. and is expected to bring dangerously cold conditions to more than half of the country. Winter weather and winter storm alerts are in effect across more than a dozen states. David Begnaud and WCBS chief weathercaster Lonnie Quinn report.
title: Arctic blast slams U.S., snow hammers states from Midwest to New England

description: L.A. Police Chief Jim McDonnell tells CBS News correspondent Jonathan Vigliotti about his biggest concerns as ICE protests in Los Angeles continue, talks about the "different mission" the National Guard is focused on and outlines the police department's protocols.
title: L.A. police chief says National Guard has a "different mission" as protests continue

description: Supreme Court justices will hear arguments Tuesday in a challenge to the Trump administration’s effort to end the DACA program, which shields nearly 700,000 young immigrants from deportation. Carter Evans spoke to former Homeland Security Secretary Janet Napolitano, who oversaw DACA during the Obama administration. He also talked with a student whose future hinges on the courts decision.
title: DACA recipient says SCOTUS decision could "destroy and erase everything"

description: A new report shows Americans' retirement savings are not growing at the same pace as stocks, which are again hovering around record highs. Over the last decade, the average 401(k) account balance grew about 124 percent, while the Dow skyrocketed 214 percent. CBS News business analyst Jill Schlesinger joins “CBS This Morning” to offer financial advice.
title: Why retirement plans aren't matching pace of market growth

description: The streaming wars are escalating, with Disney+ launching Tuesday. It's the latest streaming service competing with industry leaders, like Netflix and Hulu. CBS has CBS All Access and Apple TV+ also premiered this month. Jonathan Vigliotti reports.
title: Streaming wars escalate with Disney+ launch

description: A California man cited and handcuffed for eating a sandwich on a BART train station platform is now getting an apology. The dust-up was caught on video last week. BART says Steven Foster refused to present the officer with his ID and cursed at him. The transit agency faced mounting backlash over the encounter.
title: BART apologizes to California man handcuffed for eating sandwich on platform

description: Fourteen fraternities at San Diego State University are under suspension Tuesday after the death of a 19-year-old freshman, Dylan Hernandez, following a frat party last week. Jamie Yuccas reports.
title: Did misconduct at San Diego State University fraternity lead to student death?

description: The Supreme Court hears arguments Tuesday on the DACA program, which could lead to the deportation of nearly 700,000 young immigrants known as "Dreamers." The program protects undocumented immigrants brought to the U.S. as children, but President Trump ordered an end to it two years ago. Lower courts blocked that move. Jan Crawford reports.
title: Supreme Court weighs fate of DACA program

description: A CBS News poll on impeachment shows Americans are still split ahead of Wednesday's first public hearings. Nancy Cordes reports on the Democrats’ and Republicans’ strategies.
title: CBS News poll: Americans still split on impeachment of President Trump

description: Israel says it killed a commander in the Palestinian militant group, Islamic Jihad, in a targeted airstrike at his Gaza City home. That strike came as Islamic Jihad said another one of its commanders was targeted by Israel in the Syrian capital of Damascus. Militants in Gaza responded by firing dozens of rockets into Israel. Elizabeth Palmer reports.
title: Israel says it killed Islamic Jihad leader in Gaza

description: Former President Jimmy Carter is due to have brain surgery Tuesday in Atlanta. The 39th president has had a series of falls this year, and doctors say that has led to severe swelling. Mark Strassmann reports.
title: Jimmy Carter hospitalized to undergo brain procedure

description: Public impeachment hearings beginning this week; Helping military veterans battle PTSD.
title: 11/11/19: CBSN Evening News

description: Tips on keeping safe on Venmo, including what to do if you receive an unexpected payment or request from a stranger.
title: Venmo safety tips for avoiding scams and protecting your privacy

description: FitOps is a non-profit helping veterans find new purpose in civilian life through fitness. It's already helped veteran Randy Lloyd, who served in Iraq. He shared his story with "CBS Evening News" anchor Norah O'Donnell.
title: FitOps Foundation helping veterans transition to civilian life

description: Sen. Tammy Baldwin (D-Wisconsin) pressed Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth Wednesday on what provision in the Constitution gave President Trump the authority to send Marines to Los Angeles in response to protests there. See the moment.
title: Watch: Baldwin grills Hegseth on what authority Trump has to send Marines to L.A.

description: The proposed rollback of emissions regulations is part of the Trump administration's efforts to repeal rules that aim to address climate change.
title: EPA proposes rollback on rules limiting emissions from fossil fuel power plants

description: The White House says American and Chinese negotiators have agreed on the framework for a trade deal. CBS News' Ed O'Keefe reports.
title: Questions remain over U.S.-China trade deal

description: Time marches on, even for royalty. As the hit Netflix series "The Crown" returns for its third season, the young and glamorous Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip, played to critical acclaim by Claire Foy and Matt Smith, are out; the more mature Olivia Colman and Tobias Menzies are in. Mark Phillips spent time on the set with Colman and Helena Bonham Carter (who co-stars as Princess Margaret), and with series creator and writer Peter Morgan, to discuss the show about a family in extraordinary circumstances.
title: "The Crown": A new cast takes the throne

description: "During Hollywood's Golden Age, German immigrant Marlene Dietrich electrified audiences, defying the expectations of traditional women's roles in her films and in her life. And when the United States went to war, so did Marlene Dietrich. But it was her fiercely patriotic support for her adopted homeland that led Adolf Hitler to label her a traitor. Mo Rocca previews an excerpt from the audiobook of "Mobituaries." To hear this special episode in full, go to art19.com.
title: "Mobituaries": Marlene Dietrich goes to war

description: Dealing with death is simply part of living life, as every person who dies leaves behind loved ones who must face a grieving process. And while most of us eventually adapt to a "new normal," one in 10 endures what researchers calls "complicated grief." For them the acute phase of grief never lets up. Susan Spencer investigates the study of grief with Dr. Katherine Shear, and how a website, Modern Loss, is sharing personal stories of grief, loss and coping from around the world, sometimes with unexpected twists. She also talks with columnist Leslie Gray Streeter, who wrote the loss of her husband and came up with a surprising response to her grief.
title: With deepest sympathy: Addressing grief

description: On November 10, 1871 the Scottish explorer Dr. David Livingstone, who'd disappeared in Africa while searching for the source of the Nile, was found by Henry Stanley, a reporter for the New York Herald. Jane Pauley reports.
title: Almanac: "Dr. Livingstone, I presume?"

description: In this web exclusive, the former U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations, Nikki Haley, addresses President Donald Trump's abandonment of the Kurds in Syria who have been key in America's fight against ISIS, and the purpose of deploying U.S. troops overseas.
title: Nikki Haley: We should have the backs of the Kurds

description: In this web exclusive, the former U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations, Nikki Haley, addresses President Donald Trump's use of the term "invasion" when speaking of immigrants.
title: Nikki Haley: Trump isn't the only one guilty of inflammatory rhetoric

description: "Sunday Morning" takes us to the North Fork of the Clearwater River in north-central Idaho, where Kokanee Salmon are running. Videographer: Hank Heusinkveld.
title: Nature: Salmon

description: Weinstein was convicted of one of two counts of criminal sexual assault. The jury told the judge they hadn't reached a verdict on the third degree rape charge.
title: Harvey Weinstein guilty of criminal sexual assault as jury reaches partial verdict

description: Major changes are coming to Instagram. Starting next week, the social media platform will start hiding likes. The company is testing whether reducing popularity contests will make a safer online environment for users.
title: Instagram to hide "likes" from users starting next week

description: An Oklahoma woman is free Saturday night after 15 years behind bars for child abuse — abuse that was inflicted on her kids by her boyfriend. Mark Strassmann reports.
title: Oklahoma woman released from prison after serving 15 years behind bars for boyfriend's abuse of children

description: The federal government is taking action to fight the vaping crisis. President Trump wants to raise the age to purchase e-cigarettes from 18 to 21. The move comes amid new findings that recent vaping related illnesses and deaths are linked to vitamin E acetate. Danya Bacchus reports.
title: Trump suggests raising the vaping age to 21 to combat vaping crisis

description: Nine Americans, including six children, have now been laid to rest in the wake of that deadly ambush in Mexico. The brutality of the killings has shed new light on the soaring violence just south of the border. Manuel Bojorquez reports.
title: Ambush killings shed new light on the growing violence in Mexico

description: Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent hit back at Rep. Richard Neal during a House hearing, claiming the Democrats "voted for the biggest blowout for the deficit in history." "So I find it very difficult to be lectured to by people who created the largest deficit in history."
title: Watch: Bessent blames Democrats for creating "largest deficit in history"

description: From the Midwest to New York, wind chill made it feel like temperatures in the teens. This week,  300 cities across the country could set record lows — 20 to 30 degrees below normal. And in Erie, Pennsylvania, folks are digging out from their first snowfall of the season.
title: Winter chill impacts Midwest and New York with below normal temperatures

description: President Trump address impeachment hearings Saturday, suggesting his release on the White House summary of another call to Ukraine's president Tuesday. The public hearings kick off Wednesday — and the Democrats are leading with the man they believe is their strongest witness, Ambassador William Taylor. Weijia Jiang reports.
title: Trump retaliates against impeachment proceedings, toys with releasing Ukraine call summary

description: The lawyer for former National Security Adviser John Bolton says he has pertinent information about meetings with Ukraine. The Wall Street Journal's Siobhan Hughes joins CBSN to explain how House Democrats and Republicans are preparing for open impeachment inquiry hearings.
title: John Bolton's lawyer says he has "relevant information"

description: President Trump claims that the U.S. and China have struck a trade deal, pending final approval by him and Chinese President Xi Jinping. CBS News' Kelly O'Grady and Olivia Rinaldi have more.
title: What we know about the U.S.-China apparent trade deal

description: Germany is marking 30 years since the fall of the Berlin Wall. CBS News journalist Anna Noryskiewicz spoke with CBSN from Berlin about the Wall's lasting legacy.
title: Germany marks 30 years since fall of Berlin Wall

description: For over two decades, Carol Dodge has pursued justice for her daughter Angie, who was murdered in the summer of 1996 in Idaho Falls, Idaho. Learn how the family is helping others.
title: A 23-year fight for justice inspires hope for others

description: An overnight curfew has been imposed in downtown Los Angeles as anti-ICE protests continue in the city. CBS News correspondent Elise Preston reports.
title: What to know about ongoing ICE protests, curfew in Los Angeles

description: After 23 years, Idaho Falls, Idaho, detectives finally had a solid DNA lead in Angie Dodge’s murder case. CeCe Moore and Parabon NanoLabs’ research led them to Brian Dripps. Police just needed to collect his DNA to make certain. They traveled 300 miles to Caldwell, Idaho, and spent upwards of 24 continuous hours following Dripps, patiently waiting for him to toss a cigarette butt so they could test it.
title: How police collected a suspected killer’s DNA without him knowing

description: Kobe Bryant’s legendary mindset and work ethic helped the NBA's third all-time leading scorer win five championships, an Olympic gold medal and a guaranteed spot in basketball's hall of fame. It's also the same mindset he's taken into "retirement." Dana Jacobson reports
title: Kobe Bryant wants to be known as a storyteller

description: White House press secretary Karoline Leavitt is claiming that most of the protesters in Los Angeles have been violent, pushing back on questions at the White House press briefing about the mostly-peaceful protests in California over ICE raids. Leavitt also said that President Trump supports Americans' First Amendment right for peaceful protests.
title: Leavitt claims majority of Los Angeles protesters are violent, says Trump supports peaceful protests

description: Thirty years ago, the Berlin Wall, one of the most enduring symbols of the Cold War in Europe, came down piece by piece. That pivotal moment promised a more unified, democratic world, but decades later, that expectation has faded with the rise of nationalism and cracks appearing in the European Union and NATO. Roxana Saberi reports.
title: 30 years after fall of Berlin Wall, expectation of unity has faded

description: Cassidee Dabney's father was a wildlife biologist, and she spent much of her childhood moving among the country's national forests. That's where she learned to appreciate nature's bounty at the peak of freshness. Her culinary career also kept her on the move at worldwide locations of the Four Seasons hotel group. She's now executive chef at The Barn at Blackberry Farm outside Knoxville, Tennesee, where the menu includes produce grown right on the restaurant grounds. description:
After a night out, two women were dumped outside hospitals by masked men.  Were the men good Samaritans or did they play a role in the women’s deaths?  "48 Hours" contributor Jonathan Vigliotti reports.

CASE UPDATE: On Feb. 4, 2025, David Pearce was found guilty of first-degree murder in the deaths of Christy Giles and Hilda Marcela Cabrales. Jurors also found Pearce guilty of seven counts of sexual assault for prior charges. The case against Brandt Osborn was declared a mistrial by the judge after jurors were deadlocked on a verdict.
